<font color="#FF0000">ART BARTEL</font><br>
<tt>Sun Mar 23  4:38:27 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I know a guy named Arthur Bartel who was a pilot in Vietnam. He later became the mayor of the city I live in: Hanford, California. You can still see red flakey skin on his arms which he got from agent orange. He described how the mechanics that worked on the planes were on drugs, and often after they repaired a plane, there were parts left over, and they would just forget about it. One morning, he got up at 4 a.m. and went to eat their cold spagetti. That day, he and his best friend were supposed to bomb a bridge. He was actually eager to get on with the mission, because the planes had air conditioning, and the was the only time he could cool off and dry out. His friend gave him a thumbs up as they walked to the planes. There were two planes with two people each. As they reached the bridge, he put out his cigarette. It was like, here we go, no big deal. Then he looked out and saw what looked like a telephone pole rising vertically from the clouds right at him. He flipped the plane over to avoid it, and pulled some rediculous number of g's, which he feels the effects from to this very day. He could hear the popping the rivets as the plane's effective weight topped 35,000 pounds. As he stablized himself, he glanced to his friend's plane in time to see flames coming from the tail. He could see his friend in the other cockpit give him an uneasy thumbs up. At that instant, his friend's plane exploded in a fireball. He radioed back that he saw no parachute. He described how when he first reached Vietnam, the pilots themselves had to put up the tents in the mud and the thundering rain. He described how once when he was at a bar, he saw that a Vietnamese prostitute, who was really a young girl, had a handgun in her purse. She was acting strangely and he asked the bartender to see if she was alright. Then she went to the restroom, and they heard a gunshot. He still has the bomber jacket which still contains dozens of things that are supposed to enable you to survive in jungle in case you have to bail out: knives, water, etc. Everything is tied together with string in case the jacket becomes shredded while you're bailing out or plummeting through the atmosphere. Bartel was always against the war, but he was in the military long before anyone ever heard of Vietnam. The Kennedy assassination took place while he was out on survivalist training. 
